    "accord2title": "What is the cause of gum disease?",
    "accord2": "<p>The most important cause of gum disease is the sticky and colorless film layer called 'bacterial dental plaque' that accumulates on the teeth. Removing dental plaque with daily brushing and using dental floss is the basic requirement for a healthy mouth. If the plaque is not removed from the teeth effectively, it turns into an irregular and permeable structure known as tartar or tartar. Harmful products released by bacteria in plaque cause irritation in the gums. Because of these products, the fibers that tightly bind the gum to the tooth are destroyed, the gingiva moves away from the tooth and a periodontal pocket is formed. Thus, it becomes easier for bacteria and their products to move to deeper tissues. As the disease progresses, the pocket deepens, bacteria deeper; It progresses to the bone and destruction begins in the alveolar bone that supports the tooth. If the disease is left untreated, eventually the teeth will shake and even extractions may be required.</p>",
    "accord3title": "How is gum disease prevented?",
    "accord3": "<p> The most important task in preventing periodontal disease falls on the person himself. In order to maintain the teeth in a healthy condition, bacterial dental plaque must be removed with daily oral care procedures (tooth brushing and using dental floss). It is equally important to visit the dentist regularly. </p> <p> Daily oral care procedures can minimize the formation of tartar but may not prevent it completely. It is necessary to evaluate the areas that cannot be reached by a toothbrush, dental floss or other cleaning tools by a dentist in order to remove the existing dental plaque and / or tartar. </p>",
    "accord4title": "What is the treatment for gum disease?",
